        <li class="comment staff"><!--  -->
        
        <div class="ttmeta">
        <h3>
        <a id="comment-user-3418" href="/users/peter/">
        Peter Upfold</a></h3>
        <img class="avatar" src="http://www.gravatar.com/avatar/45266ec596a8acb0905a065dbe7ed453?s=65&amp;d=identicon" height="65" width="65" />
        
    
    <div>
    <div id="reply"><a href="#reply-3418" class="button replylink">Quote</a></div>
    </div>
    </div>


<div class="ttpost">
	<div class="ttmeta-more">
		<a name="c3418" href="#c3418">#</a>
		Posted on <strong>07 June 2009</strong> at <strong>12:21 PM</strong>
	</div>
	<p><a href="#c3417">Tim Jeffries said</a>:
</p>
<blockquote><p>Is there any way to use this command from Mac OS X? I'm being told that the command isn't found ... :-(
</p>
</blockquote><p>curl ships with Mac OS X, but wget unfortunately does not. You can either <a href="http://www.asitis.org/installing-wget-for-mac-os-x">compile it yourself</a> or there is a pre-built version in a zip archive available at <a href="http://www.statusq.org/archives/2008/07/30/1954/">the Status-Q blog</a>. In the latter case, you can simply copy the wget binary in that zip archive to /usr/local/bin, or anywhere else in your PATH.
</p>
	<br class="clear" />
</div>
<br class="clear" />
</li>


    
